args: The evacuations are nearly complete,\nwhich means it's time for us to withdraw.
You need to try and eat something before\nwe leave, so I took it upon myself to\nmake a little treat just as you did for me.
It looks rather a mess, but I think you'll\nfind it tastes good all the same.
I'll leave it here, but don't force yourself to\neat if you don't want to. I'm sure it will\ncome out better the next time I make it.
I heard about what happened to Ignacio,\nso I understand why you're closing up\nlike this right now.
You have always tried to take the weight\nof the world on your shoulders, and I've\nno doubt you blame yourself for his death.
You likely believe that if he had stayed\nthe same timid man he was previously,\nhe would still be alive.
But do you really think Ignacio saw his\ntransformation as a bad thing?
Change itself is not bad. Yes, it may be\nsad or difficult sometimes, but it can be\nhappy as well.
I'm certain Ignacio understood that,\nso the fact you changed him is—
Sounds like the fiends are back!
I need to go, Sheila. We can continue\nthis conversation when I return.
(How can he say change isn't bad?\nHow can you possibly embrace it?)
(I couldn't ever think that way; there's not\na single new thing about me that I'm\nhappy about.)
(It hurts to see my father and all those\nclose to me growing old and weak.)
(This town is nothing like the town\nI once knew...)
(Also, I hate that I get hungry now!\nI just want to be full forever.)
(I finally met a friend again after all\nthese years...)
(But if this is what happens when things\nchange, there's nothing good about it!)
And I know you still blame yourself for my\nhusband's death, but you must let that go.
He was grateful to you to the very end,\nfor you gave him the opportunity to be\nthe hero he always wanted to be.
Yet if he didn't change, he'd still be alive.\nSo how can he possibly thank me?
My husband wanted to be brave, which is\nwhy he fought to protect everyone.
And while he couldn't fight with your skill,\nhe could help those who needed to escape.
I know my husband's efforts made a\ndifference, even if it was a small one.
You gave him the push he needed to\ntransform himself, which is why so many\nof us are still alive today.
So please don't say you regret the things\nhe's grateful for. Don't say you regret the\nfact we're still alive!
My husband was overjoyed with the new\npath his life took, so please don't take\nthat away from him!
But change doesn't have to be a sad\noccasion. In fact, it can be joyous!

But nothing can stay the same forever.
No matter how badly you wish it to not
be so, everything moves on—including
you and me.
Change itself is not bad. Yes, it may be\nsad or difficult sometimes, but it can be\nhappy as well.
I'm certain he understood that. So Sheila,\nthe fact that you changed him is—
*sigh* I guess my hunger doesn't care\nwhether it's an appropriate time or not.
There's no end to these fiends,\nbut I can't let up now!
You cooked the caramel too long.\nThat makes it bitter.
Apparently you ate my crème brûlée.
I think I understand now that change may\nnot be the terrible thing I thought it was.
Nothing can stay the same forever, so I\nneed to make sure that what DOES change\ndoes so for the better.
So as soon as I'm done cleaning up these\nfiends, I'm going to teach you how to make\na decent dessert.
Ha! In that case, let's take care of this\npack double-quick!
I am so sorry you had to go through that.\nI can't thank you enough.
We should be the ones thanking you.
Your words gave me the strength\nto embrace change.
So if you ever run into any trouble,\njust say the word and I will be there.
You really are just like my husband said...\nWell, we should be off now.
I'm not gonna cry anymore, even without\ncandy. And some day I'm gonna be a hero!
I see I'm not the only one turning over a\nnew leaf. I wish you the best of luck, Nico.
Hee hee! Okay, see ya later! Byeeee!
We should head out as well.
